# A Comprehensive Survey of Multimodal Large Language Models: Architectures, Training, and Evaluation

## Abstract

The rapid advancement of Large Language Models (LLMs) has catalyzed a paradigm shift in artificial intelligence, extending beyond text to encompass **vision**, **audio**, and **structured data** modalities. This survey provides a comprehensive analysis of 127 multimodal LLMs published between January 2024 and March 2026, categorizing them across four architectural families: (1) early fusion, (2) late fusion, (3) cross-attention, and (4) mixture-of-experts (MoE). We establish a unified evaluation framework spanning 23 benchmarks and identify critical gaps in current approaches including *hallucination mitigation*, *spatial reasoning*, and *long-context multimodal understanding*.

**Keywords:** multimodal, large language models, vision-language, survey, benchmark

## 1. Introduction

The integration of multiple modalities into language models represents one of the most significant developments in AI research since the introduction of the Transformer architecture [[ref:section:2.1]]. Early work by Radford et al. [^1] on CLIP demonstrated that contrastive pre-training could align visual and textual representations, achieving zero-shot transfer competitive with supervised baselines on ImageNet. Subsequent efforts — including Flamingo [^2], BLIP-2 [^3], and LLaVA [^4] — progressively closed the gap between modality-specific specialists and generalist multimodal systems.

This survey differs from prior reviews in three key respects:

1. **Scope**: We cover 127 models (vs. 43 in the most recent prior survey), including 38 published in 2026
2. **Depth**: Each model is evaluated across our unified 23-benchmark framework, enabling direct comparison
3. **Practicality**: We provide concrete recommendations for practitioners choosing between architectures for specific deployment scenarios

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Section 2 covers background ([[ref:section:2]]), Section 3 presents our taxonomy ([[ref:section:3]]), and Section 4 reports experimental results ([[ref:section:4]]).

## 2. Background and Related Work

### 2.1 Transformer Architecture

The Transformer [^5] introduced the self-attention mechanism, computed as:

$$\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\left(\frac{QK^T}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V$$ {math: latex}

where $$Q \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times d_k}$$ {math: latex}, $$K \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times d_k}$$ {math: latex}, and $$V \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times d_v}$$ {math: latex}.

### 2.2 Vision Encoders

Modern vision encoders fall into three categories:

||| table id="t-encoders" caption="Table 1: Vision Encoder Comparison"
| Encoder Family  | Representative Models          | Resolution | Params   | ImageNet Top-1 |
|-----------------|--------------------------------|------------|----------|----------------|
| ViT-based       | ViT-L/14, SigLIP-SO400M       | 224–384    | 304M–1B  | 88.6%          |
| ConvNeXt        | ConvNeXt-XXL, InternImage-H   | 384–512    | 600M–1B  | 89.1%          |
| Hybrid          | CoAtNet-7, MaxViT-XL          | 384–512    | 700M–2B  | 89.4%          |
| Native Res.     | NaViT, FlexiViT, AnyRes-ViT   | Any        | 300M–1B  | 88.2%          |
|||

