|||

## 5. Discussion

### 5.1 Key Findings

Our analysis reveals several critical insights:

1. **Architecture matters less than scale** — at comparable parameter counts, early fusion and cross-attention models achieve similar performance (within 2% average score)
2. **MoE models offer the best efficiency** — DeepSeek-VL2 achieves 79.5 avg score with only 28B active parameters (vs. 72B+ for comparable dense models)
3. **Resolution is the bottleneck** — models supporting dynamic resolution (AnyRes, NaViT) consistently outperform fixed-resolution counterparts by 3-5% on document understanding tasks
4. **Hallucination remains unsolved** — even the best models hallucinate on 8-15% of detailed visual questions

### 5.2 Open Problems

- **Spatial reasoning**: Performance drops 15-25% on tasks requiring precise spatial relationship understanding
- **Long-context multimodal**: No model maintains quality beyond 32K combined tokens (visual + text)
- **Temporal understanding**: Video-language models lag image-language models by 10-20% on equivalent tasks
- **Verifiability**: No model provides confidence calibrated to actual accuracy

## 6. Conclusion

This survey has provided the most comprehensive analysis of multimodal LLMs to date, covering 127 models across four architectural families. Our unified 23-benchmark evaluation framework enables direct comparison and reveals that scale, data quality, and resolution flexibility are the dominant factors in model performance. We release our evaluation data and benchmark toolkit at `https://github.com/mllm-survey/benchmark-2026`.

## References

[^1]: Radford, A. et al. "Learning Transferable Visual Models From Natural Language Supervision." ICML 2021.

[^2]: Alayrac, J.-B. et al. "Flamingo: a Visual Language Model for Few-Shot Learning." NeurIPS 2022.

[^3]: Li, J. et al. "BLIP-2: Bootstrapping Language-Image Pre-training with Frozen Image Encoders and Large Language Models." ICML 2023.

[^4]: Liu, H. et al. "Visual Instruction Tuning." NeurIPS 2023.

[^5]: Vaswani, A. et al. "Attention Is All You Need." NeurIPS 2017.

